         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers2090">
               <p>John Anthony was the oldest son of <persName>Anthony</persName> and <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2091.xml"/>Mary (Goldhawk) Vazeille</persName>. He is
                  apparently the son that <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"
                     />JW</persName> describes in a letter to <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2091.xml"/>Mary</persName> dated <date
                     when="1774-07-15">July 15, 1774</date> as having been &apos;a grievous
                  cross&apos; to her. He is almost certainly the son-in-law that <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> tells <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers1405.xml"/>Lady Maxwell</persName> in a letter dated
                     <date when="1788-08-08">Aug. 8, 1788</date> had been a physician for a while,
                  but left that profession. In <date when="1768">1768</date> he was in
                     <placeName>India</placeName> as a member of the Bengal army of the East Indies
                  Company, from where he wrote to his mother. By <date when="1788">1788</date>, when
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> wrote
                        <persName><ref target="/persons/pers1405.xml"/>Lady Maxwell</persName>, he
                  was deceased.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
   </text>
